<p>Magic number Au13 nanoclusters stabilized entirely  by  N-heterocyclic carbenes (NHCs)  have  been prepared by the  bottom-up  reduction of  well-defined molecular NHC–Au–Cl complexes with sodium borohydride. The  nature  of the wingtip  groups was shown  to be  critical  in the preparation of  stable  clusters. The all NHC-clusters are prepared in high yield by this straight-forward method, display higher stability than related all phosphine  clusters,  and  possess  extremely high  emission quantum yield. DFT analysis of these clusters based on the resolved crystal structure reveals their electronic structure as 8-electron superatoms.</p>
